  "audio_duration_secs": 54.14,
  "text": "Turning written notes into a deck usually means fighting formatting, resizing slides, and cleaning up exports. Slide Builder takes plain markdown and turns it into a finished presentation while you write. You type on the left, the deck renders live on the right, and it sticks to the same simple convention people already use for content-to-slides: slide breaks, titles, body copy, done.\n\nThe nice part is you\u2019re not choosing from one or two skins. There are 19 presets here, including six house styles and the canonical content-to-slides looks, all organized in a gallery with named font pairings loaded right into the exported deck. And the output is locked to the viewport, so slides fit phones, tablets, and full-size screens without awkward scrolling or text spilling off the page.\n\nWhen it\u2019s ready, you ship one self-contained HTML file with the CSS and JavaScript embedded, no dependencies, no server round-trip, and it still works offline. That means the distance between rough markdown and a deck you can actually send is basically gone.",
  "asr_text": "Turning written notes into a deck usually means fighting formatting, resizing slides, and cleaning up exports. Slide Builder takes plain markdown and turns it into a finished presentation while you write. You type on the left, the deck renders live on the right, and it sticks to the same simple convention people already use for content to slides. Slide breaks, titles, body copy, done. The nice part is you're not choosing from one or two skins. There are 19 presets here, including 6 house styles and the canonical content to slides looks, all organized in a gallery, with named font pairings loaded right into the exported deck. And the output is locked to the viewport, so slides fit phones, tablets, and full-size screens without awkward scrolling or text spilling off the page. When it's ready, you ship one self-contained HTML file, with the CSS and JavaScript embedded, no dependencies, no server roundtrip, and it still works offline. That means the distance between rough markdown and a deck you can actually send is basically",
